In [Sass Usage](https://github.com/twbs/bootstrap-sass#sass-1)
```sass
$navbar-default-bg: #312312;
$light-orange: #ff8c00;
$navbar-default-color: $light-orange;

@import "bootstrap";
```

Importing [bootstrap](https://github.com/twbs/bootstrap-sass/blob/master/assets/stylesheets/_bootstrap.scss) will override the custom variables by importing the variables again.
```sass
// Core variables and mixins
@import "bootstrap/variables";
@import "bootstrap/mixins";

// Reset and dependencies
@import "bootstrap/normalize";
...
```

So the custom variables will not be overridden.

#### Solution
The solution to override is to have a file that does the work of bootstap.sass and have the variables included there. Eg.,
*custom-bootstrap.sass*
```sass
// Core variables and mixins
@import "lib/bootstrap/variables";
@import "lib/bootstrap/mixins";

// Overriding variables
@import "custom-variables";

// OR
$navbar-default-bg: #312312;
$light-orange: #ff8c00;
$navbar-default-color: $light-orange;


// Reset and dependencies
@import "lib/bootstrap/normalize";
...
```

When reading from a pipe, ExaBGP is not updating the nexthop of a route. The neighbor is IBGP.

For example:
We start ExaBGP and print to the pipe:
"neighbor 2001::4 announce route 2605::2/128 next-hop 2001::1 local-preference 500"

We then announce the same route, but with a different nexthop (2001::2 instead of 2001::1):
"neighbor 2001::4 announce route 2605::2/128 next-hop 2001::2 local-preference 500"

At this point, ExaBGP still has the nexthop as the first one that was sent.

This only happens with IPv6 route announcements, over both IPv4 and IPv6 BGP sessions. tcpdump confirms there is no UPDATE message sent.

IPv4 route announcements works just fine with a very similar config (just changing family to ipv4 unicast and peering over an IPv4 session). Ee can change the nexthop of an IPv4 route with no issues.

Tested on 3.4.11.

Our scripts and configs bellow (IPs have been anonymized):

